<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-550-661  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 550 661.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 29 1990 v7 n43 p191(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Creative marketing drives Borland growth. (Borland InternationalInc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ould, Andrew.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Borland International Inc. (Sales statistics).andO;Ticker:    BORL.andO;Product:   Paradox (Data base management system) (Market share)Quattro Pro (Spreadsheet software) (Market share).andO;Topic:     SalesSecond QuarterSoftware PublishersMarket SharePromotion of ProductPrice.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Andrew OuldandM;Borland International Inc. is bucking the industry slowdown.andM;The Scotts Valley, Calif., company reported a 109 percent jump in sales and a112 percent increase in profits for its second quarter, ended Sept.andP;  30.andP;  Thecompany's two flagship programs -- the Quattro Pro spreadsheet and Paradoxdatabase -- are both gaining market share at the expense of Lotus DevelopmentCorp.'s 1-2-3 and Ashton-Tate's dBASE, according to a recent report fromNeedham andamp; Co., a New York investment firm.andM;Quattro Pro, unveiled last November, has captured 25 percent of the PCspreadsheet market, and Paradox has about 20 percent of the PC databasemarket, according to the report.andM;Charlotte Walker, an analyst with Labse, Simpson andamp; Co., a New York investmentfirm, attributes Borland's performance to a combination of &quot;very goodproducts and aggressive marketing.andP;  Borland has always been the dark horse,but it has learned to market better, tougher and more creatively.&quot;andM;Borland launched its promotional assault on Lotus last November by offeringQuattro Pro to 1-2-3 customers for $99.95.andM;The firm now has turned its marketing sights on Microsoft Corp.andP;  Last weekBorland offered users of Microsoft C an upgrade to Borland's Turbo C++Professional for $149.95, less than half the suggested retail price.andM;Walker said Borland's success is also due to what is &quot;probably the largestregistered user base in the industry.&quot;andM;But Philippe Kahn, Borland's president and CEO, said that &quot;it's the productsthat sell.andP;  You can't compete against a larger company with inferiorproducts.&quot;andM;Borland faces two key obstacles, including the economic slowdown.andP;  &quot;The bigquestion I have is whether Borland can maintain its growth in the face ofslowing PC sales,&quot; said Timothy McCollum, an analyst with stock brockerageDean Witter Reynolds Inc., in New York.andM;Kahn said he has seen no sign of a slowdown and predicts &quot;tremendous growth.&quot;andM;Another concern is the copyright infringement suit Lotus filed againstBorland in July.andP;  But Kahn said the suit has had no effect on Borland or onsales of Quattro Pro.andM;He also predicts a victory in court.andP;  &quot;We believe Quattro Pro does notinfringe on Lotus' copyrights,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;We believe we'll prove that incourt and that Lotus will look silly.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>